. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]},{"name":"Millicent","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Melisende</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>amal</i> ‘labour’ + <i>swinth</i> ‘strength’. This was the name of a daughter of Charlemagne. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":18,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Millicent DeBeckering Bekeryne was born in 1437, in Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England. She married John Burdon in 1457, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1497, in Towcester, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1437–1497":"1437–1497","1433–1493":"1433–1493","1455–1506":"1455–1506","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1497":"1497","about 1455":"umbes 1455","1493":"1493","1506":"1506","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Burdonesoldebury Lancaster Trowbrugge, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England",", Nottingham, England, Great Britain":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England":"Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1437–1497":"1437–1497","1433–1493":"1433–1493","1455–1506":"1455–1506","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1497":"1497","about 1455":"noin 1455","1493":"1493","1506":"1506","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Burdonesoldebury Lancaster Trowbrugge, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England",", Nottingham, England, Great Britain":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England":"Holme Pierrepont, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"1437–1497":"1437–1497","1433–1493":"1433–1493","1455–1506":"1455–1506","1437":"1437","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1497":"1497","about 1455":"environ 1455","1493":"1493","1506":"1506","Towcester, Northamptonshire, England":"Towcester, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","Burdonesoldebury Lancaster Trowbrugge, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Angleterre",", Nottingham, England, Great Britain":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Holme Pi